"problem_statement": "Find the smallest prime p such that there exists an integer n satisfying n^4 + 1 ≡ 0 (mod p^2), and then find the smallest positive integer m satisfying the same congruence.",
"steps": [
{
"step_number": 1,
"description": "Find the smallest prime p such that n^4 + 1 ≡ 0 (mod p). For n^4 ≡ -1 (mod p) to have a solution, the order of n modulo p must be 8. By Fermat's Little Theorem, 8 must divide p-1, so p ≡ 1 (mod 8). The candidate primes are 17, 41, 73, 89, 97, ...",
"result": "p ≡ 1 (mod 8)"
},
{
"step_number": 2,
"description": "Check p = 17. We need to see if n^4 + 1 ≡ 0 (mod 289) has a solution. First, find n such that n^4 ≡ -1 (mod 17). The solutions are n ≡ 2, 8, 9, 15 (mod 17). Using Hensel's Lemma, since f'(n) = 4n^3 is not 0 (mod 17) for these values, each solution lifts uniquely to modulo 289.",
"result": "p = 17"
},
{
"step_number": 3,
"description": "Find the smallest m such that m^4 + 1 ≡ 0 (mod 289). This requires calculating the specific lifts for n ≡ 2, 8, 9, 15 (mod 17) to find the minimum positive integer m.",
"result": "In progress"
}
],
"conclusion": "The smallest prime p is 17."
}
}

